            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Linear algebra toolbox – FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <article class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >How should I interpret the determinant being “very small”
                      but not exactly zero?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700 hidden">
                    If the determinant is tiny relative to the scale of the
                    entries, the matrix is <em>nearly singular</em>.
                    Numerically, this means solving Ax = b or computing A<sup
                      >−1</sup
                    >
                    will be sensitive to rounding and data errors. The toolbox
                    flags such situations by using a small tolerance when
                    deciding whether a pivot is effectively zero.
                  </div>
                </article>

                <article class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >What does it mean if the tool says that the system Ax = b
                      is inconsistent?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700 hidden">
                    An inconsistent system is one where no vector x satisfies
                    all the equations simultaneously. In row-echelon form, this
                    appears as a row of the form [0 0 … 0 | c] with c ≠ 0 in the
                    augmented matrix [A | b]. In that case, the tool reports
                    that the system has no solution under the given numeric
                    tolerance.
                  </div>
                </article>

                <article class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
